---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHead from '../components/PageHead.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Octopad — Quick Start" page="quickstart">
  <PageHead
    kicker="Quick Start"
    heading="Getting Started<br/>with Octopad."
    lede="This guide walks you through how Octopad works, from setup to your daily rhythm. No prior knowledge assumed."
  />

  <section class="wrap">
    <div class="docs">
      <nav class="toc" aria-label="On this page">
        <a href="#overview" class="active">1 — What Octopad is in 60 seconds</a>
        <a href="#setup">2 — Set up</a>
        <a href="#context">3 — How your AI finds the right context</a>
        <a href="#work">4 — How work is organized</a>
        <a href="#handshake">5 — The "use octopad" handshake</a>
        <a href="#day">6 — Running your day</a>
        <a href="#octobots">7 — Our little helpers in the background</a>
        <a href="#chain">8 — Chain with your other tools</a>
        <a href="#mindset">9 — The right mindset, and what's next</a>
      </nav>

      <article>
        <blockquote>
          <strong>Shortcut worth knowing:</strong> once your AI is connected,
          you can ask it anything you read here. "What is a work stream?"
          "How do I capture a decision?" Your AI already knows. This guide is
          the printed backup. Your AI is the live tutor.
        </blockquote>

        <h2 id="overview">1 — What Octopad is in 60 seconds</h2>
        <p>
          Octopad is your AI's back-office: your strategy, your tasks, your
          plans, your decisions, and your team's know-how, all in one shared
          brain your AI can read, write, and work from.
        </p>
        <p>
          You work mostly by talking to your AI. The AI creates tasks, wires
          dependencies, captures decisions, writes pages, ties work to
          strategy. The Octopad interface is a control panel where you see
          what your AI does and steer when needed. You can click around and
          build things by hand, but the AI is the faster path and produces
          richer output for the same effort.
        </p>
        <p>
          Why this matters. A normal AI chat has no back-office. Every new
          conversation starts cold. Octopad gives every session a shared brain
          with everything your team has captured, and a structured place to
          capture what comes next. Nothing gets re-explained. Nothing gets
          lost.
        </p>

        <h2 id="setup">2 — Set up</h2>
        <p>Seven small moves. About five minutes.</p>
        <p>
          <strong>Sign up.</strong> Free, no credit card. Head to
          <code>octopad.app</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Follow the onboarding.</strong> It walks you through
          connecting your AI and setting up your workspace. Come back here
          when it's done.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Open your first chat and say "use octopad."</strong> Start a
          new conversation with your AI and type it exactly:
          <strong>"use octopad."</strong> Your AI connects to your workspace
          and is ready to work inside Octopad. Your workspace is still mostly
          empty; you're about to fill it.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Give your AI information about your company and your
          product.</strong> In that same chat, share the basics. Your AI turns
          what you share into pages inside Octopad, typically a Product
          Overview and a Company Overview. These become your first reference
          documents.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Turn on "add to workspace context" for those pages.</strong>
          As a workspace admin, flip the toggle on your Product Overview and
          Company Overview. Every teammate's AI will now load those summaries
          at the start of every session, so no one on the team has to
          re-explain the basics. (There's a per-user version of the toggle
          too, for pages you only want in your own context.)
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Verify it loads.</strong> Close that chat and open a fresh
          one. Say "use octopad" and ask a question about what you just
          shared: "what does our product do?" or "who are we building for?"
          Your AI should read it back.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Set your first strategy.</strong> Ask your AI to create at
          least one goal and one work stream. For example: a goal like "Launch
          our beta by June 30" and a work stream under it called "Marketing
          Website." Goals and streams are how your AI understands where any
          task fits. A task on its own is just a line item. A task inside a
          stream, under a goal, has purpose.
        </p>

        <h2 id="context">3 — How your AI finds the right context</h2>
        <p>
          Your AI's context in Octopad sits in three systems, working
          together. Your AI handles them for you. Knowing what's under the
          hood helps you get more out of the product.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Pages.</strong> Long-form documents. This is where your core
          reference content lives: Product Overview, Company Overview, Brand
          Guidelines, strategy notes, research, meeting notes, anything your
          AI should be able to pull from later. Every page gets an
          auto-generated summary, so your AI can skim the index before opening
          any page in full.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Key Information.</strong> Short, atomic items. Four kinds: a
          fact ("we ship on Fridays"), a decision ("we chose Stripe over
          Paddle for native payouts"), an open question ("do we need SOC 2
          before Q4?"), and a risk ("our top competitor just raised"). Your
          AI captures these automatically as they come up in conversation, and
          pulls the relevant ones back when it picks up a task later.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Build Context.</strong> The engine that assembles the right
          material for each job. When you ask your AI to work on a task, it
          calls build context. That pulls the task description, its
          dependencies, its linked pages, related key information, the tracker
          page for its work stream (more on trackers in the next section), and
          additional page chunks that match the task semantically, even if
          they were never linked directly. Your AI shows up already briefed.
        </p>
        <p>
          An example. You ask your AI to start working on the "Create the
          pricing page" task. Build context loads the task, your Brand
          Guidelines page, last week's Value Propositions page, the decision
          about positioning you captured on Monday, and a few relevant chunks
          from other pages in your workspace. Your AI starts writing already
          knowing everything you know.
        </p>

        <h2 id="work">4 — How work is organized</h2>
        <p>Four concepts, stacked from biggest to smallest.</p>
        <p>
          <strong>Organizations and Workspaces.</strong> An organization is
          your company. Workspaces live inside it. You invite people at the
          org level, then grant them access to specific workspaces.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>We suggest starting with one workspace.</strong> Context
          isn't shared across workspaces yet, so one workspace keeps
          everything in one brain. You can always split later.
        </p>
        <p>
          Roles are simple. At the org level: <strong>Owner</strong> (full
          control, including deleting the org), <strong>Admin</strong>
          (invites members, creates workspaces, manages settings),
          <strong>Member</strong> (access only to workspaces they're
          explicitly invited to). Inside each workspace:
          <strong>Admin</strong> (manages members and integrations) and
          <strong>Contributor</strong> (creates and edits everything: tasks,
          pages, knowledge).
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Goals.</strong> What you're trying to achieve and why.
          Quarterly or yearly. For example: "Launch our beta by June 30."
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Work Streams.</strong> How you get there. A stream is a
          project or an area of work. Two flavors:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Ongoing streams</strong> never close. They cover permanent
            areas like "Customer Support" or "Content."
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Time-bound streams</strong> have a target date and a
            finish line. They sit under a goal, for example "Marketing
            Website" under "Launch our beta by June 30."
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Every stream gets an auto-generated <strong>tracker page</strong>
          that logs activity and progress summaries on its own. You don't
          update it by hand.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Tasks.</strong> The unit of work. Each task has a Why (the
          problem), a What (the scope), and a How (the approach, when it's
          non-obvious). Your AI also adds a "Done when" line so you know when
          it's really finished. Tasks have priority, impact, can have
          subtasks, and can depend on other tasks with a one-line rationale so
          the order is never mysterious.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>A note on task standards.</strong> Your AI follows a
          template when it creates tasks, which is why they're richer than
          what you'd type by hand in a hurry. The template isn't
          user-customizable yet. We're always looking to make Octopad better,
          so if you want to change what the template includes, tell us.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>AI score.</strong> Every task gets a score. It combines
          priority, impact, deadline pressure, and where the task sits in the
          dependency chain. It surfaces what's most important to work on next,
          so you don't have to scan the whole backlog. Read it as a useful
          recommendation.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Automatic rituals.</strong> When a task closes, your AI
          writes a completion comment: what shipped, why that approach, any
          follow-up. When a time-bound stream finishes, your AI writes a
          closing report. These compound. A month in, your workspace is a
          real record of what got done and why.
        </p>
        <p>
          A full example. You're launching the beta of your product. Goal:
          "Launch our beta by June 30." Work stream under it: "Marketing
          Website." Tasks inside: "Write the homepage copy," "Set up email
          capture," "Record the demo video," "Publish the site." Subtasks
          break the bigger ones down. Dependencies wire the order ("Write the
          homepage copy" before "Record the demo video," since the video
          echoes the copy). Your AI picks what to work on next based on the
          score. You can always override.
        </p>

        <h2 id="handshake">5 — The "use octopad" handshake</h2>
        <p>
          Every new chat with your AI starts cold unless you tell it
          otherwise. Say <strong>"use octopad"</strong> at the start of any
          fresh conversation and your AI loads a package from your workspace
          before doing any real work.
        </p>
        <p>What's in the package:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Your core pages (the ones you toggled into workspace context).</li>
          <li>A quick strategy briefing: your active goals and your open work streams.</li>
          <li>A short recap of your last three sessions, so your AI knows what you were doing recently.</li>
          <li>The Octopad playbook: how to capture decisions, how to create good tasks, when to update a tracker, how to close things out. This is what keeps your AI consistent across conversations.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          When to say it. Every time you start a new chat with your AI, before
          you ask for any real work. If you forget, your AI will still try,
          but the quality drops because it's flying without the briefing.
        </p>

        <h2 id="day">6 — Running your day</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Your to-do list.</strong> Your personal, ordered queue of
          what you're working on now. Two ways to fill it. Ask your AI to
          generate it ("what should I work on today?") and it picks up to
          five tasks based on priority, dependencies, and deadlines. Or pin
          specific tasks yourself ("add the homepage copy task to my to-do
          list").
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Resume one thing.</strong> Say
          <strong>"resume working on my to-do list"</strong> and your AI runs
          you through the queue in order. Say
          <strong>"resume working on the homepage copy"</strong> to jump
          straight to one task. If that task has subtasks, your AI
          automatically picks the right next one. You don't need to specify.
        </p>

        <h2 id="octobots">7 — Our little helpers in the background</h2>
        <p>
          Octopad has a small fleet of always-on AI agents we call
          <strong>octobots</strong>. They run in the background and keep your
          workspace tidy without anyone triggering them. A few examples:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Session Scribe</strong> writes a short summary of what
            happened every time a session ends, so the next one picks up
            cleanly.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Page Summarizer</strong> keeps every page's summary fresh
            as you edit, so your AI can skim before diving in.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Stream Activity Logger</strong> writes one entry per work
            stream every time something changes, so your tracker pages stay
            current.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Work Stream Reconciler</strong> runs nightly and
            compresses the day's activity into a clean progress report on each
            active stream.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          You don't interact with them. They just do their job. We're
          actively building more to take even more routine work off your plate
          and make the system smarter over time.
        </p>

        <h2 id="chain">8 — Chain with your other tools</h2>
        <p>
          Octopad is one connector in a bigger picture. Your AI can talk to
          many other apps the same way: Slack, Gmail, GitHub, Tiny Fish, your
          calendar, and more. When you connect more than one, your AI can
          work across all of them in a single conversation.
        </p>
        <p>Three examples you can say out loud to your AI today:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <em>"Scan our #product channel in Slack for anything that should
            become a task in Octopad."</em> Your AI reads the last week of
            messages, picks what's actionable, creates tasks in the right
            stream, and links back to the original messages.
          </li>
          <li>
            <em>"Create a task for John to review the pricing page, then send
            him a Slack message explaining why I'm assigning it."</em> Your AI
            creates the task in Octopad, then sends John a short message in
            Slack with the context, so he knows the what and why before he
            even opens Octopad.
          </li>
          <li>
            <em>"Ask Tiny Fish to run a competitor analysis and log the
            findings to a page in Octopad."</em> Tiny Fish runs the research;
            your AI takes the results and writes them up as a page in the
            right stream, with sources attached.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Each of these is one sentence. No copy-paste between tabs, no
          "where did I save that." Your AI becomes the connective tissue
          between your tools, and Octopad is where the durable context lives
          so nothing falls through the cracks.
        </p>

        <h2 id="mindset">9 — The right mindset, and what's next</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>AI-first.</strong> Octopad is designed so you talk to your
          AI, and the interface catches what the AI does. You can absolutely
          click around and build things by hand, but when you ask your AI to
          do it, you get richer descriptions, better-linked pages, cleaner
          dependencies, and captured decisions, all for the same amount of
          effort on your part. Treat the interface as a control panel: a
          place to see, steer, and occasionally click.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Your AI is the tutor.</strong> Anything in this guide, your
          AI can explain on demand. Ask: "what is a work stream?" or "how
          does build context work?" or "how do I archive a task?" If
          something feels confusing, the answer is one sentence away.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Tell us what's missing.</strong> If something doesn't make
          sense, if you wish Octopad worked differently, or if your AI is
          missing a capability, tell us. There's a feedback button in every
          workspace.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<script>
  const links = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLAnchorElement>('.docs nav.toc a');
  const heads = Array.from(links).map((a) => {
    const href = a.getAttribute('href');
    return href ? document.querySelector(href) : null;
  });
  const setActive = (i: number) =>
    links.forEach((l, k) => l.classList.toggle('active', k === i));
  const io = new IntersectionObserver(
    (entries) => {
      for (const e of entries) {
        if (e.isIntersecting) {
          const i = heads.indexOf(e.target);
          if (i >= 0) setActive(i);
        }
      }
    },
    { rootMargin: '-88px 0px -70% 0px', threshold: 0 },
  );
  heads.forEach((h) => h && io.observe(h));
</script>
